decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">U.S. securit=
ies law</a>, an investment contract is =E2=80=9Cthe investment of money in =
a common enterprise with a reasonable expectation of profits to be derived =
from the efforts of others,=E2=80=9D which is, straightforwardly, what this=
 is.=C2=A0An investment contract is a type of security, and a security is s=
ubject to regulation by the Securities and Exchange Commission. If you sell=
 securities to the public, you generally have to register them with the SEC=
, deliver a prospectus, have audited financials, etc. Or you can sell them =
under some exemption from those rules =E2=80=94=C2=A0for instance, if you o=
nly sell them to non-U.S. persons, or if you only sell them to =E2=80=9C<a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24693311.258647/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDktMjQvZWFybmlu=
Zy10aGUtcmlnaHQtdG8tZ2V0LXN3aW5kbGVk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa7434f11" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">accredited in=
vestors</a>=E2=80=9D (meaning, roughly, rich people). It seems to me that i=
t would be quite inconvenient for DeFi to be subject to these rules, and th=
at a lot of people in the DeFi world would prefer to be exempt from them, o=
r ignore them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, if you=C2=A0<em>don=E2=
=80=99t=C2=A0</em>replace the words =E2=80=9Csmart contract=E2=80=9D with t=
he word =E2=80=9Cperson,=E2=80=9D I am not=C2=A0<em>quite=C2=A0</em>sure th=
at what you have is a security under U.S. law. Perhaps you could argue that=
 the workings of the smart contract are not =E2=80=9Cthe efforts of others=
=E2=80=9D: Sure the smart contract was=C2=A0<em>written=C2=A0</em>by some p=
rogrammer, but its operation is (let=E2=80=99s assume) deterministic and op=
en-source; you are (arguably) not investing money because you trust the pro=
grammer to do something but because you can read the code and know what it =
will do. You are not funding a business but putting money into a machine th=
at makes money come out; you can examine all the moving parts of the machin=
e, see how it works, and trust in that rather than in =E2=80=9Cthe efforts =
of others.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t k=
now that that=E2=80=99s a very good argument =E2=80=94=C2=A0I do not think =
that the=C2=A0<em>SEC=C2=A0</em>would agree with=C2=A0it =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=
, you know, it=E2=80=99s an argument; it=E2=80=99s interesting. Also there =
is the practical point that if investors put their cryptocurrency into a po=
t controlled by a smart contract, it is not controlled by=C2=A0<em>people</=
em>, so there is =E2=80=94=C2=A0not quite =E2=80=9Cnobody for the SEC to su=
e,=E2=80=9D it could sue the programmers who wrote the contract or the peop=
le who promoted it on social media, but there is not really an=C2=A0<em>iss=
uer=C2=A0</em>of the security to sue in the same sense that there would be =
for a stock offering by a company. The point here is that there is some gen=
uine novelty in DeFi; it is really unlike the sorts of securities offerings=
 that were on Congress=E2=80=99s mind when it passed the core U.S. securiti=
es laws in the 1930s. But it is=C2=A0<em>mostly analogous=C2=A0</em>to thos=
e offerings, so there is going to be trouble.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
24693311.258647/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS0=
xNDU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfec6d08f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">an SEC action against a DeFi protocol</a> fro=
m last Friday:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities a=
nd Exchange Commission today charged two Florida men and their Cayman Islan=
ds company for unregistered sales of more than $30 million of securities us=
ing smart contracts and so-called =E2=80=9Cdecentralized finance=E2=80=9D (=
DeFi) technology, and for misleading investors concerning the operations an=
d profitability of their business DeFi Money Market.=C2=A0 =C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, Gregory Keough=
, Derek Acree, and their company Blockchain Credit Partners offered and sol=
d securities in unregistered offerings through DeFi Money Market from Febru=
ary 2020 to February 2021. The order finds that they used smart contracts t=
o sell two types of digital tokens: mTokens that could be purchased using s=
pecified digital assets and that paid 6.25 percent interest, and DMG =E2=80=
=9Cgovernance tokens=E2=80=9D that purportedly gave holders certain voting =
rights, a share of excess profits, and the ability to profit from DMG gover=
nance token resales in the secondary market.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">The defendants settled by paying back $12.8 million that the=
y raised and agreeing to fines of $125,000 each. The <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24693311.258647/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdv=
di9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjEvMzMtMTA5NjEucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0=
2c37ebd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">S=
EC order</a> is worth reading for its legal analysis of DeFi protocols. Thi=
s protocol involved two tokens, one paying a fixed rate and another =E2=80=
=9Cgovernance token=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">T=
hey sold two types of digital tokens: mTokens, which accrued 6.25% interest=
, and DMG tokens, which were so-called =E2=80=9Cgovernance tokens=E2=80=9D =
that purportedly gave DMG token holders certain voting rights, a share of e=
xcess profits, and the ability to profit from DMG resales in the secondary =
market. Respondents promised to pay a stable interest rate to digital asset=
 owners who purchased mTokens and said they could generate excess profit fo=
r DMG token owners. During the Relevant Time Period, they sold approximatel=
y $17.7 million in mTokens and more than $13.9 million in DMG tokens to the=
 public, including U.S. investors.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The governance tokens =E2=80=9Cwere offered and sold as investment con=
tracts and thus were securities,=E2=80=9D says the SEC, and I don=E2=80=99t=
 know how you could argue otherwise. This is not the sort of DeFi protocol =
where everything operated automatically and deterministically; the =E2=80=
=9Csmart contracts=E2=80=9D involved here governed the investors=E2=80=99 i=
nvestments and the promoters=E2=80=99 draws on those investments, but once =
the promoters took the money they made decisions about how to invest it to =
try to maximize profits. So, sure, securities.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">The 6.25%-interest mTokens are a bit of a harder question, because you =
could argue that those are not an =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract=E2=80=9D but=
 rather just a=C2=A0<em>loan</em>. If I borrow money from you at a fixed in=
terest rate, that is not necessarily a security, even if I use the money to=
 fund some harebrained get-rich-quick scheme. But the SEC argues that these=
 tokens are =E2=80=9Cnotes,=E2=80=9D and the kind of note that counts as a =
security:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A note is presumed to=
 be a security unless it falls into certain judicially-created categories o=
f financial instruments that are not securities, or if the note in question=
 bears a =E2=80=9Cfamily resemblance=E2=80=9D to notes in those categories =
based on a four-part test. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Applyi=
ng the <em>Reves</em> four-part analysis, the mTokens are securities. First=
, Respondents sold mTokens to raise funds for the general use of its busine=
ss, namely to purchase income-generating assets to pay interest on redeemed=
 mTokens and excess interest to DMG token holders, and purchasers bought mT=
okens solely to earn 6.25% interest on their digital assets. Second, mToken=
s were offered and sold to the general public. Third, Respondents promoted =
mTokens as an investment, specifically as a way to earn a consistent return=
 of 6.25% on digital=C2=A0assets. Fourth, no alternative regulatory scheme =
or other risk reducing factors exist with respect to the mTokens.</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This seems like bad news for DeFi lendi=
ng protocols. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24=
693311.258647/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
jEtMDctMjEvamFtaWUtZGltb24tZ290LWEtYm9udXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB95e1107=
c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote =
last month</a> about a state enforcement action against BlockFi, another De=
Fi-ish lending protocol that raised crypto from investors and loaned it out=
 to users. =E2=80=9CI suppose the question,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cis whether the interest accounts are=C2=A0<em>pooled investments</em>=C2=
=A0(in proprietary trading or lending operations) or just=C2=A0<em>loans to=
 BlockFi denominated in Bitcoin</em>, which would not be a security.=E2=80=
=9D But the SEC says, nope, even if the thing is just a loan to the DeFi pr=
otocol, that=E2=80=99s a =E2=80=9Cnote=E2=80=9D and counts as a security.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway this is an important case in the deve=
lopment of the securities regulation of DeFi, but also separately the facts=
=C2=A0here are kind of funny? The basic idea of this scheme was that invest=
ors would deposit Ether in the DMM smart contract, and DMM would use it to =
make car loans or something and pay 6.25% interest. But the problem is that=
 no one borrows Ether to buy a car; they borrow dollars. If you borrow $20,=
000 to buy a car and pay 7% interest, someone could package that into a not=
e, pay 6.25% on the note, and have a bit of extra money to pay profit inter=
ests. But there=E2=80=99s a problem if=C2=A0<em>the note is denominated in =
Ether</em>. If the price of Ether doubles, and you pay back the $20,000, th=
at isn=E2=80=99t enough Ether to pay back the note. Oops!</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometime after publicly unveiling DMM, Responden=
ts realized that their vision of using digital assets to purchase income-ge=
nerating assets faced a significant roadblock: how to account for fluctuati=
ons in the value of the digital assets. While the assets Respondents intend=
ed to purchase would generate sufficient income to pay interest, there was =
a significant risk that the income would not be sufficient to cover appreci=
ation of investors=E2=80=99 principal given a substantial increase in the p=
rice of volatile digital assets, such as Ether.</p></blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">More than securities laws, this is a real problem with bu=
ilding a new financial system on top of cryptocurrency: If you use crypto t=
o fund real-world assets, and the price of every cryptocurrency is constant=
ly doubling and halving, every loan repayment is chaos.</p><table class=3D"=
